from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder

# Assuming 'sub' dataframe contains the relevant data
# If 'sub' is not defined in your code, replace it with the appropriate dataframe

# Filter dataframe to include only rows with "Heavyweight" weight class
sub_heavyweight = sub[sub['weight_class'] == 'Heavyweight']

# Initialize LabelEncoder
encoder = LabelEncoder()

# Encode 'weight_class' to numerical format
sub_heavyweight['weight_class_encoded'] = encoder.fit_transform(sub_heavyweight['weight_class'])

# Add the four new factors to the sub_heavyweight dataframe
sub_heavyweight['R_Height_cms'] = sub['R_Height_cms']
sub_heavyweight['R_Reach_cms'] = sub['R_Reach_cms']
sub_heavyweight['B_Height_cms'] = sub['B_Height_cms']
sub_heavyweight['B_Reach_cms'] = sub['B_Reach_cms']

# Compute correlation matrix including the encoded weight_class and the new factors
corr_matrix = sub_heavyweight.corr()

# Plot heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 10))
heatmap = sns.heatmap(corr_matrix, annot=True, cmap="coolwarm")
heatmap.set_title('Correlation Heatmap for Heavyweight with Additional Factors', fontdict={'fontsize': 18}, pad=12)
plt.show()
